Connecticut
--------------
<http://dep.state.ct.us/mosquito/index.asp> [edited
17 Aug 2000
The State announced 11 additional WNV positive birds including 10 crows and
one robin: from Milford (2 crows); Fairfield (4 crows); Stamford (3 crows,
one robin); and West Hartford (one robin). To date, 50 birds have tested
positive for WNV -- 49 crows and one robin -- in 15 different communities.
16 Aug 2000
The State of Connecticut Mosquito Management Program announced a positive
isolation of West Nile Virus (WNV) in bird-biting mosquitoes collected from
the area of Cranbury Park in Norwalk. Collected on 7 Aug 2000, the pool of
mosquitoes that tested positive was _Culex restuans_, a bird-biting
mosquito. See the Test Results for Mosquitoes/Birds page or your town page
for more detailed information.
--
[We thank H. Larry Penning <bevpenn@fgi.net> for also sending us this
mosquito report from a news source yesterday. Â– Mod.JW
*****
New Jersey
-------------
<http://www.state.nj.us/health/cd/westnile/810results.htm> [edited
17 Aug 2000
To date, 165 birds (164 crows and a cockatiel) found in 9 counties have
tested positive for the presence of WNV. Positive birds have been found in
Bergen (51), Essex (10), Hudson (18), Middlesex (40), Monmouth (13), Morris
(1), Passaic (17), Somerset (1) and Union (14) counties. Negative birds
have been found in these and all other counties. The tests were conducted
at the Department of Health and Senior Services' lab in Trenton: the CDC
confirmed early season results.
*****
New York City
-------------
<http://www.ci.nyc.ny.us/html/doh/html/public/press00/pr75-815.html> [edited
17 Aug 2000
New York City Health Commissioner Neal L. Cohen, M.D., announced this
morning that 23 mosquito pools from Staten Island, 3 mosquito pools from
Central Park, Manhattan, one mosquito pool from Hunts Point in the Bronx,
one crow from Northern Manhattan, one crow from Central Park and one crow
from Whitestone, Queens have tested positive for West Nile virus. These
findings were reported to the City Health Department yesterday by the New
York State Department of Health. As a result of this information, the City
will apply pesticides to reduce the number of potentially infected
mosquitoes at several locations citywide over the next several days.
The total number of WNV-infected birds identified in New York City to date
include: 44 (28 in Staten Island, 5 in Manhattan, 4 in Queens, 1 in the
Bronx, and 6 in Brooklyn). In addition, WNV has been confirmed in 52 pools
of mosquitoes (44 in Staten Island, 6 in Manhattan, 1 in the Bronx and 1 in
Queens).
*****
New York State
-------------------
<http://www.health.state.ny.us/nysdoh/westnile/update/today.htm> [edited
17 Aug 2000
Today, the New York State Health Department's Wadsworth Laboratory reported
14 West Nile virus positive mosquito pools: Orange County, 1; Rockland
County, 4 and Suffolk County, 9.
The total number of West Nile virus positive specimens for New York State
this year is 213 birds, 128 mosquito pools, 1 sentinel chicken, 5 live wild
birds and 3 human cases.
Note: Another species of infected mosquito was included in yesterday's
data. The species, _Aedes triseriatus_, is among the most common tree-hole
and container-breeding mosquitoes in New York State. This mosquito bites
primarily at dawn and dusk and will feed on humans.
--
Date: Thu, 17 Aug 2000 10:51:35 -0400
From: Rose, Robert <Robert_Rose@URMC.Rochester.edu>

A dead blue jay found earlier this month in Livingston County in western
New York State, due south of the City of Rochester, has tested positive for
West Nile virus. Results were announced yesterday by the state health
department laboratory.
